West 36th Street (foreground), and east of the S.E. corner of Eleventh Ave. (extreme right), showing various aspects of the major track removal program of the New York Central Railroad; a portion of the West Side Improvement Project. The former R.H. Macy warehouse is shown in a state of metamorphosis, the understructure of which has been rebuilt to permit the railroad tracks in the rock cut to pass underneath and thereby join those in the yard on the westerly side of the Avenue. The photographer is viewing in a southwestward direction from a point on the north side of 36th Street alongside of the aforementioned road bed.

June 25, 1937.

Gift of New York Central System Publicity Bureau.

West Side Improvement Project: A northward view from West 36th Street of the new road bed of the New York Central Railroad tracks on the easterly side of Eleventh Ave., connecting the 34th and 60th Street yards. This is a part of the Railroad Company's contribution to the above project; for further views of same, see files under individual locations and items.

June 25, 1937.

Gift of New York Central System
Publicity Bureau.
title: West Side Improvement Project.

text:
West Side Improvement Project: A northward view from West 36th Street of the rock cut carrying the New York Central Railroad tracks from the 34th Street yard to the 60th Street yard, both of which are on the westerly side of Eleventh Ave., though the new roadway parallels the easterly side of same. Construction necessitated the demolition of numerous buildings and the excavating of 25 feet of solid rock. This was a portion of the New York Central Railroad's contribution to this vast improvement bearing the above title, for further views, see files for individual locations and items.

June 25, 1937.

Gift of New York Central System Publicity Bureau.
